cards.flavor_text: [i]As one gets further away from the center of the Holt, the Wonderlands grow colder and more mountainous, then completely impassable at the plane's edge.[/i]
[i]Where the Holt begins to slope downwards into the Deepmists, the sky is lit by a brilliant, permanent aurora before a starless twilight backdrop.[/i]
[i]In a coffin of blinding fog and perfect silence, the embalmed corpse of a beloved world rests.[/i]
[i]The patchwork walls are engraved with symbols of dead gods and scriptures in forgotten languages, their meaning lost to all but the Citadel itself. [/i]
[i]Hidden within the dense jungle of the inner Holt are doors to the Citadel, which present themselves only to the brazen.[/i]
[i]Patches of alien, flat-topped trees dot the outer Holt, their prodigious size owing to the life force concentrated in pools below their roots. [/i]

[i]The atria of the Citadel are its most dangerous areas, not because of any efforts by the plane itself, but due to scavengers fighting to strip the walls' near-limitless supply of precious metals.[/i]
[i]The Ilcans crested the hill to find cool, clean air and soft ground for the first time in years.[/i]
[i]Chance-in-Hell had won the same battle countless times over... but this time, as she waited in the ashes for it all to reset, she saw something new.[/i]
[i]The Tensu explorers were puzzled to find that the clearing seemed to disappear from certain angles, a vibrant new space bleeding through.[/i]
[i]It was Manuela that found the hidden path to the edge of the starry sky, but it was Aechmi that realized that the shapes in the stardust mirrored the Deepmists' winding maze.[/i]
[i]Chance-in-Hell had blasted her way through the bedrock of the Holt and the floor of the Citadel, but found that the barriers to the Worldsoul were more subtle than stone.[/i]
[i]The Citadel is almost completely barren of residents compared to the Holt. A few solitary wanderers remain, miring in their memories of the dead planes its halls are built from.[/i]
[i]New Tensuo settled on top of a landscape of warped rock, unaware of the apocalypse that had transformed Dhere's home plane into that landscape two centuries ago.[/i]

[i]“People from many planes come through here, and they worship many gods. For my part, I preserve the shrines as best I can.”
—Dhere, lone wanderer[/i]

[i]“Just one of them grows enough flesh to feed five people, and it all grows back in a week.”
—Aechmi, Ilcan wanderer[/i]
[i]A few years after the invasion left Ilcae ruined, the Wonderlands overlaid itself onto patches of the plane, rewriting its oil-stained ground into fresh grass and vibrant color overnight.[/i]
[i]The structure of the Wonderlands is ever-shifting, and its motivations are inscrutable.[/i]

[i]“The Ilcans are violent, and we don't know what they're capable of. Keep the peace until we do.”
—Amarell, elder of New Tensuo[/i]
[i]“There are so many ways for a world to die in this Multiverse.”[/i]
[i]When it roosts for the final time, it will be reborn as something beautiful.[/i]
[i]The arrival of the Wonderlands attracted the desperate and the curious, but most of all it attracted those seeking to take its power.[/i]
[i]The Ilcans and New Tensuo were both sure of one thing: the other one wanted to pick a fight.[/i]

[i]“Fire has only one wish, and it's been granted.”
—Ovueli, New Tensuo mage[/i]
[i]For just a moment, a near-forgotten face and a reassuring voice.[/i]
[i]With New Tensuo unwilling to share its smithing infrastructure, most others have to get creative.[/i]

[i]“Oh, it's nothing... just thought I saw someone.”
—Manuela Martinez[/i]

[i]“Another meteor. Damn place is taunting me.”
—Chance-in-Hell[/i]
[i]“Yes, yes, of course I know the path to the Citadel. Not too much longer now.” [/i]

[i]“What was this plane before the Wonderlands?”
—Fieldbook of Manuela Martinez[/i]

[i]“He was weak. Forget him. Remain steady.”
—Ajha, the Wish for Home[/i]
[i]When Hana died in the Holt, she was overjoyed to wake up unharmed in her bed... until the next day, when she saw herself limping back down the path.[/i]
[i]“The Wonderlands won't grant [/i]my [i]wish, so it's up to you bloodbags to pick up the slack.” [/i]
[i]She had forgotten the reason for her resentment for the living, but the plane still enabled it.[/i]

[i]“It's not that I don't care, it's just... I haven't had a life away from the sword for so long, and this place can give me that.”
—Nenwe, Ilcan survivor, to Ajha[/i]
[i]Introduced by New Tensuo to ward off native wildlife, the prelwort adapted to become more of a nusiance than they ever were.[/i]
[i]When Chance-in-Hell turned her attention to them both, the planeswalkers felt like candle flames at the bottom of the ocean. [/i]
[i]“I can't believe my luck! The Multiverse is real, and I get to explore it!”[/i]

[i]“For a moment, I could read it—every secret the world has ever kept from me, before the portal closed. I will not rest until I find it again.”
—Evelyn, Wonderlands researcher[/i]
[i]Remnants of old settlements dot the outer Holt, their positions shifting and dwindling with time.[/i]
[i]The second layer of the Wonderlands, accessible through deep caves and mysterious doors, is a vast web of jumbled architecture.[/i]

[i]“Remain steady. This plane wants us to forget their faces, wants to slow us down, but it can't. We will know no peace until Ilcae lives again.”
—Ajha, the Wish for Home[/i]
[i]Though she took the credit for crafting it, Hana couldn't help but question why the plane allowed her to stumble upon a sword that repelled its own creations.[/i]

[i]“Keep the Ilcans focused on small victories. They cannot be trusted to wield true power.”
—Amarell, elder of New Tensuo[/i]
[i]“Not quite sure what you want out of this brave new world? Let me pick.”[/i]

[i]Manuela took a shuddering breath as Chance-in-Hell knelt by the body, staring her down with a bright smile. “That was a warning shot. Step out of line, or try and skip town, and I'll kill the rest of ‘em too.”[/i]

[i]“Even a noble desire should be tempered.”
—Amarell, elder of New Tensuo[/i]
[i]“We have all we want now. Why fight?”[/i]

[i]“Nobody around for him to hurt. Not the happiest wish, but I can't blame him for making it.”
—Dhere, lone wanderer[/i]
[i]The last of a plane, she, and it, are immortalized by the Wonderlands' sympathy.[/i]

[i]“Oh, good, your plane has science fiction. That'll make my friend here much easier to explain.”
—Eteres, planar analyst[/i]
[i]The survivors of Ilcae, battle-hardened and fueled by grief, tear through the Wonderlands in desperate hope for a wish to resurrect their plane.[/i]

cards.rules_text:
Tap two untapped creatures you control: Manuela becomes a 5/5 Avatar enchantment creature with indestructible until end of turn. Activate only as a sorcery.
[+1]: Put your choice of a +1/+1 counter or a menace counter on up to one target creature.
[-2]: Exile target nonland permanent. Its owner may cast it without paying its mana cost on a later turn as long as it remains exiled.
[-5]: Draw three cards, then discard a card.

cards.flavor_text:
[i]“It's hard to live in the present when everything around you is a reminder of the past.”
—Dhere, lone wanderer[/i]
[i]The pantheon of Tensuo is as hierarchical and rigid as its leadership.[/i]

[i]“Cease all progress, Ajha, or this will be war.”
—Amarell, elder of New Tensuo[/i]

[i]“Lucky for you, you're not the first planeswalker I've met. The first two, I hadn't yet figured out that you don't get their sparks after you kill them.”
— Chance-in-Hell, to Manuela Martinez[/i]
[i]Manuela knew she had only minutes before Chance-in-Hell caught up to her, but that was time enough to tell Ajha the way to the Worldsoul.[/i]
[i]While the Ilcans and Tensu are the united factions of the Holt, most of it is controlled by ruthless individuals from a wide range of planes, seeking to exploit the Wonderlands.[/i]

[i]“Dreams are getting more vivid, and I never used to wake up so energized. Is this safe?”
—Fieldbook of Manuela Martinez[/i]

[i]“You seem like a smart guy. Wanna join up?”
—Chance-in-Hell [/i]
[i]The gramophone creaked to life, and Manuela and Eteres strained to hear the tired voice. “This was the plane of Ischav,” it began.[/i]

[i]“Who made these carvings? How accurate was their understanding of the plane's mechanics?”
—Fieldbook of Manuela Martinez[/i]

[i]“Is there any pattern to the permanent aurora?”
—Fieldbook of Manuela Martinez[/i]

[i]“It lost a loved one, and it's trying to heal.”
—Eteres, planar analyst[/i]
[i]“This plane is a truly marvelous ecosystem, able to sustain friends from a hundred worlds.”[/i]
[i]The Ilcans' initial violent distrust of the beings of Wonder led New Tensuo to see them as savages.[/i]

cards.special_text2:
[-1]: Each opponent loses 3 life, discards a card, and sacrifices a nonland permanent.
[-X]: Exile target card from a graveyard with mana value X. You may cast a copy of that card without paying its mana cost.
[-3]: Look at the top six cards of your library. Put up to three of them into your hand and the rest into your graveyard.

cards.flavor_text: [i]The Wonderlands granted its simple desire by allowing it to drink from the sky itself.[/i]
[i]The space spasmed and lurched around Manuela and Chance-in-Hell, and suddenly they were alone somewhere incomprehensible.[/i]

[i]“Respect the denizens of the Holt, but do not fear them. These lands provide for their needs, so if one wants something from you, it won't be your flesh.”
—Amarell, elder of New Tensuo[/i]
[i]Every inch of its surface is covered in text that is just on the cusp of readability. [/i]
[i]“Remain steady. I owe it to them.” [/i]

[i]“It is a great and callous power here, one that grants wishes born of hope and hatred in equal measure. We must tread lightly.”
—Amarell, elder of New Tensuo[/i]
[i]The center of the Wonderlands cradles her.[/i]
[i]The elder council of New Tensuo were far too slow to realize the danger Chance-in-Hell posed, and by the time they acted, she was already done with them.[/i]

[i]“This place sees that we miss them, but it can't always bring them back. I don't think it knows that we hate what it tries to replace them with.”
—Aechmi, Ilcan wanderer[/i]
[i]“The armor wasn't built for this climate, but... it might be the only suit left of its kind.”[/i]
[i]Mutual hatred tempered by lust for power is a decent substitute for teamwork.[/i]

[i]“The beings of Wonder seem to have no written language, so whose language is on the stones?”
— Fieldbook of Manuela Martinez[/i]

[i]“Are the walls moving, or is the space itself?”
—Fieldbook of Manuela Martinez[/i]

[i]“What [/i]was [i]this thing? How did it [/i]do[i] that?”
—Fieldbook of Manuela Martinez[/i]

cards.rules_text:
Cathexis, Soul Aspect enters with an additional loyalty counter on it for each unique name among other permanents you control.
[-1]: You may sacrifice a permanent. If you do, create a 5/5 Wonder Archon creature token that's all colors. If you don't, create two 1/1 Wonder creature tokens that are all colors.
[-4]: Draw a card for each permanent you control that's two or more colors.

cards.flavor_text:
[i]“Enigmatic and silent, seen wandering the second and even third layers. Are they native to the plane, or have they just been here longer?”
—Fieldbook of Manuela Martinez[/i]
[i]Animals living in the Wonderlands grow more attuned to it over time, their size and intelligence heightening as they approach total subsumption.[/i]
[i]Wherever it came from and whatever it's learned, it's uninterested in sharing.[/i]

cards.rules_text:
When Eteres enters, search your library for any number of cards with total mana value 3 or less, exile them with study counters on them, then shuffle.
[+2]: Put a land card you own in exile with a study counter on it onto the battlefield under your control. 
[-2]: Draw a card, then you may exchange a card in your hand and a card you own in exile with a study counter on it.

cards.flavor_text: [i]For the first time, Manuela saw Ahja's confidence waver as the plane itself began to warp under the strain of granting her wish.[/i]
[i]The fourth layer of the Wonderlands, deep below and high above, is the seat of the outpouring Worldsoul itself.[/i]
[i]“Ours is the only just cause here. Our homeland must live on, and I will pay any cost, or crush any foe, to realize that dream.” [/i]
[i]Some beasts, rather than being subsumed by Wonder over time, grow into it.[/i]
[i]The Ilcan abomination was closing in, and with nowhere else to run, Wei knew that the only way to get her squad home safely was to charge.[/i]
[i]Chance-in-Hell was not alone in wanting the Tensu elders gone.[/i]

[i]“It's what I can do. I don't know how it works.”
—Manuela Martinez[/i]

[i]“Were they ever inhabited? If so, by whom?”
—Fieldbook of Manuela Martinez[/i]
[i]Olse watched the pool drain into the shape of her sister. No magic on Ilcae could revive her, even after her body was cleansed of the oil, but this power could conjure her from memory alone.[/i]
[i]There are few truly malevolent beings in the Wonderlands, but those few thrive.[/i]
[i]“It's so common to wish for more time, but nearly impossible to get it.”[/i]

[i]“I didn't know her for long, but she was so scared of death. She's not scared anymore, at least.”
—Dhere, lone wanderer[/i]

[i]“Maybe it's a good thing some planes are gone.”
—Dhere, lone wanderer[/i]
[i]The pools drained, and Ilcae was reborn.[/i]
[i]While allowing oneself to be consumed by desire is dangerous, it is embraced by the Ilcans as a means to an end.[/i]
[i]It alone keeps a story it can never tell.[/i]
[i]“I am of the first world visited by the Wonderlands, centuries ago. It has confided in me.”[/i]

[i]“It's subtle, but the plane is guiding its visitors to fixate on their own desires, rather than itself.”
—Eteres, planar analyst[/i]

[i]“The beings of this plane shine with light and mana, brilliant and tempting. I can't help but be reminded of an anglerfish's lure.”
—Fieldbook of Manuela Martinez[/i]
